paragraphs.text: %md ## OML4R Feature Extraction: Singular Value Decomposition The Oracle Machine Learning for R function ore.odmSVD creates a model that uses the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) algorithm for feature extraction. In this notebook, we demonstrate how to use the in-database SVD for feature extraction using the Breast Cancer dataset from the University of Wisconsin. We show that Principal Component Analysis (PCA) can be achieved using SVD results. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database. msg.data:
OML4R Feature Extraction: Singular Value Decomposition

The Oracle Machine Learning for R function ore.odmSVD creates a model that uses the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) algorithm for feature extraction.

In this notebook, we demonstrate how to use the in-database SVD for feature extraction using the Breast Cancer dataset from the University of Wisconsin.
We show that Principal Component Analysis (PCA) can be achieved using SVD results. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database.

Copyright (c) 2022 Oracle Corporation

The Universal Permissive License (UPL), Version 1.0

cat("Shape:", dim(MTCARS))

paragraphs.title: View the ore.odmSVD help file
paragraphs.text:
%r

help("ore.odmSVD")

msg.data:
ore.odmSVD                package:OREdm                R Documentation

In-Database Singular Value Decomposition Models

Description:

     Creates a Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) model for feature
     extraction using Oracle Data Mining in Oracle Database 12.2 or
     later.

Usage:

     ore.odmSVD(formula,                        
             data, 
             auto.data.prep = TRUE,
             na.action = na.pass,
             odm.settings = NULL,
             ctx.settings = NULL)
     
     ## S3 method for class 'ore.odmSVD'
     features(object,...)
     
     ## S3 method for class 'ore.odmSVD'
     feature_compare(object,
       newdata,
       compare.cols = NULL,
       supplemental.cols = NULL)
     
     ## S3 method for class 'ore.odmSVD'
     predict(object,
       newdata,                
       supplemental.cols = NULL,
       type = c("class","raw"),
       na.action = na.pass,
       topN = NULL,...)
     
     u(object)
     ## S3 method for class 'ore.odmSVD'
     u(object)
     
     v(object)
     ## S3 method for class 'ore.odmSVD'
     v(object)
     
     d(object)
     ## S3 method for class 'ore.odmSVD'
     d(object)
     
Arguments:

 formula: An object of class ‘formula’ (or one that can be coerced to
          that class): a symbolic description of the model to be
          fitted. For details of the model specification, see
          'Details'.

    data: An ‘ore.frame’ object used for model building.

auto.data.prep: A logical value that specifies whether Oracle Data
          Mining should invoke automatic data preparation for the
          build.

na.action: A function to use for handling missing values, either
          ‘na.pass’ to allow missing values or ‘na.omit’ to remove rows
          with missing values. The default value is ‘na.pass’.

odm.settings: Same as ‘odm.settings’ in ‘ore.odmKMeans’.

ctx.settings: Same as ‘ctx.settings’ in ‘ore.odmKMeans’.

  object: An object of type ‘ore.odmSVD’.

 newdata: The data used for scoring.

compare.cols: Columns used to compare the features.  All the columns
          are included by default.

supplemental.cols: Columns to include in the output.

    type: If set to ‘"raw"’, provides the probability for each feature
          returned. If set to ‘"class"’, the feature with the maximum
          probability is returned.

    topN: A positive integer that restricts the set of features to
          those that have one of the specified number of highest
          probability values.

     ...: Additional arguments affecting the predictions produced.

Details:

     Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) is a feature extraction
     algorithm. SVD is orthogonal linear transformations that capture
     the underlying variance of the data by decomposing a rectangular
     matrix into three matrixes: ‘U’, ‘D’, and ‘V’. Matrix ‘D’ is a
     diagonal matrix and its singular values reflect the amount of data
     variance captured by the bases.

Value:

     An object of class "ore.odmSVD" includes the following components:

    name: The name of the in-database model.

settings: A ‘data.frame’ of settings used to build the model.

attributes: A ‘data.frame’ of attributes used to build the model.

 formula: The ‘formula’ used for the model fitted.

    call: The matched call.
     The ‘d’ function returns an ‘ore.frame’ with the singular values
     of the input data. Column ‘FEATURE_ID’ represents the singular
     value ID. The ‘v’ function returns an ‘ore.frame’ whose columns
     contain the right singular vectors. The column names match with
     ‘FEATURE_ID’ values. The ‘u’ function returns an ‘ore.frame’ whose
     columns contain the left singular vectors. ‘CASE_ID_COLUMN_NAME’
     and ‘SVDS_U_MATRIX_OUTPUT’ must be specified in argument
     ‘odm.settings’ to product this result.

     The ‘features’ function returns an ‘ore.frame’ the same as the ‘v’
     function does except in an (vertical) unpivot format.  The columns
     are:

FEATURE_ID: The numeric identifier associated with the singular value.

ATTRIBUTE_NAME: The name of the attribute.

ATTRIBUTE_VALUE: The value of the attribute.

   VALUE: The coefficient value associated with the attribute in the
          new space.
     The ‘feature_compare’ function returns an ‘ore.frame’ containing a
     ‘SIMILARITY’ column and supplementary columns if specified.

Author(s):

     Oracle

     Maintainer: Oracle <email: oracle-r-enterprise@oracle.com>

References:

     Oracle R Enterprise

     Oracle Data Mining Concepts

     Oracle Data Mining User's Guide

See Also:

     ‘ore.odmNMF’, ‘ore.odmESA’, ‘partitions’

Examples:

     IRIS <- ore.push(cbind(Id = seq_along(iris[[1L]]), iris))
     
     svd.mod <- ore.odmSVD(~. -Id, IRIS)
     summary(svd.mod)
     d(svd.mod)
     v(svd.mod)
     head(predict(svd.mod, IRIS, supplemental.cols = "Id"))
     
     svd.pmod <- ore.odmSVD(~. -Id, IRIS, 
                   odm.settings = list(odms_partition_columns = "Species"))
     summary(svd.pmod)
     d(svd.pmod)
     v(svd.pmod)
     head(predict(svd.pmod, IRIS, supplemental.cols = "Id"))

paragraphs.title: Build an SVD model
paragraphs.text:
%r 

ore.exec("BEGIN DBMS_DATA_MINING.DROP_MODEL(model_name=> 'SVD_PCA_MODEL'); EXCEPTION WHEN others THEN null; END;")

svd_mod <- ore.odmSVD(~., MTCARS, auto.data.prep=TRUE, 
                      odm.settings = list(svds_scoring_mode='svds_scoring_pca', model_name = "SVD_PCA_MODEL"))

msg.data:
Warning message:
“The created mining model SVD_PCA_MODEL is explicitly named. ORE does not manage this mining model's life cycle.”

paragraphs.title: The D matrix contains the singular values
paragraphs.text:
%r

svd_d <- d(svd_mod)
rownames(svd_d) <- svd_d$FEATURE_ID

value_total <- sum(svd_d$VALUE)

svd_d <- mutate(svd_d, Percent_of_Total = 100 * (svd_d['VALUE'] / value_total))

z.show(round(svd_d, 4))

# Using the SVD model for Principal Component projections

msg.data: Using the SVD model for Principal Component projections

paragraphs.title: Drop the table if it exists
paragraphs.text:
%r 
 
tryCatch({ ore.drop(table="MTCARS_PCA_PROJECTIONS") })

paragraphs.title: Create a table that contains the projections (SQL section)
paragraphs.text:
%r 

ore.exec('CREATE TABLE MTCARS_PCA_PROJECTIONS AS 
          SELECT "drat", "disp", "hp", 
                 FEATURE_VALUE(SVD_PCA_MODEL, 1 USING *) PCA_PROJ1,
                 FEATURE_VALUE(SVD_PCA_MODEL, 2 USING *) PCA_PROJ2,
                 FEATURE_VALUE(SVD_PCA_MODEL, 3 USING *) PCA_PROJ3
          FROM MTCARS
          ORDER BY 1, 2')

paragraphs.title: Look at the PCA projections
paragraphs.text:
%r
 
ore.sync(table="MTCARS_PCA_PROJECTIONS")
ore.attach()

z.show(MTCARS_PCA_PROJECTIONS)

paragraphs.title: Original data - top 3 attributes
paragraphs.text:
%r

# Convert data to local data.frame object for plotting
ore.sync(table = "MTCARS_PCA_PROJECTIONS")
mtcars_proj_local <- ore.pull(MTCARS_PCA_PROJECTIONS)


splom(~mtcars_proj_local[,c("drat", "disp", "hp")], 
      groups = drat, data = mtcars_proj_local, panel = panel.superpose, 
      diag.panel = function(x, ...){
        yrng <- current.panel.limits()$ylim
        d <- density(x, na.rm=TRUE, bw="SJ")
        d$y <- with(d, yrng[1] + 0.95 * diff(yrng) * y / max(y) )
        panel.lines(d)
        diag.panel.splom(x, ...)
      })

paragraphs.title: SVD-PCA projections - top 3 principal components
paragraphs.text:
%r 

splom(~mtcars_proj_local[,c("PCA_PROJ1", "PCA_PROJ2", "PCA_PROJ3")], 
      groups = PCA_PROJ1, data = mtcars_proj_local, panel = panel.superpose, 
      diag.panel = function(x, ...){
        yrng <- current.panel.limits()$ylim
        d <- density(x, na.rm=TRUE, bw="SJ")
        d$y <- with(d, yrng[1] + 0.95 * diff(yrng) * y / max(y) )
        panel.lines(d)
        diag.panel.splom(x, ...)
      })
